@cheddar : I had some "magic" logic like that previously related to some other stuff, and there was concern raised by @gianm  about it.

In this particular case the most concerning part is if it is gzip, would you want it to rename the file to the base name and output to the directory, or are you wanting to pass in a file you want the ungzip'd data to go to?

There is not obvious auto-magic solution in such a case without having flags which only pertain to the gzip case.

If you want to do a count of the number of dim2 rows matching values 1 and 0  you can do so e.g. 
{
  "type" : "filtered",
  "filter" : {
    "type" : "or", 
 "filters" : [ {
    "type" : "selector",
    "dimension" : dim2,
    "value" : 1}, 
    {
    "type" : "selector",
    "dimension" : dim2,
    "value" : 0
    }]
  },
  "aggregator" : { "type" : "count", "name" : "filteredRowCount" }
}

For more complex use cases, you can also have a look at writing JavaScript aggregator with any custom logic you need.

@cheddar regarding having an option to start up a replica of some other historical nodes, it will solve the case of quickly replacing a node with a new node, however there are cases when we need to replicate/move data based on coordinator rules (for selective datasources and periods) across tiers and not just replicate a set of existing historical nodes. let me describe a concrete use cases - I am experimenting with a tier of hs1.8xlarge nodes, that can be used as a replica of existing tiers, and can be used to load up super old data for which performance is not critical, now the issue with these nodes is it takes order of a week to load up a node with 20T of data when the loading is single threaded. 

how about having an option to dynamically enable/disable/configure parallel loading of segments for a particular tier or set of nodes with the default to do single threaded loading to ensure that no existing behavior will change ? 
System admin can then tune the concurrency factor through coordinator console whenever required.

Hi again,

I have detected same problem when I add a filter on the query. I have done other test to check this case. 

``` java
    @Test
    public void nullDimensionWithFilter() {
        TopNQuery query = new TopNQueryBuilder()
                .dataSource(QueryRunnerTestHelperNull.dataSource)
                .granularity(QueryGranularity.MINUTE)
                .dimension("dot11_protocol")
                .metric("flows")
                .filters(new SelectorDimFilter("dot11_protocol", ""))
                .threshold(1000)
                .intervals("2015-04-06T09:00:00/2015-04-06T10:00:00")
                .aggregators(
                        Lists.<AggregatorFactory>newArrayList(
                                Iterables.concat(
                                        Lists.newArrayList(
                                                new LongSumAggregatorFactory("flows", "events")
                                        )
                                )
                        )
                )
                .build();

        HashMap<String, Object> context = new HashMap<String, Object>();
        Iterator<? extends Result> result = Sequences.toList(runner.run(query, context), Lists.<Result>newArrayList()).iterator();

        while (result.hasNext()){
            Result queryResult = result.next();
            TopNResultValue value = (TopNResultValue) queryResult.getValue();
            Assert.assertFalse(queryResult.toString(), value.getValue().isEmpty());
        }
    }
```

